{td}SHR-1{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-10|showSummary=false}{/td}
{td}User Story{/td}
{td}Farmer{/td}
{td}Must Have{/td}
{td}Monitor soil moisture continuously at ≤60s intervals and display live readings on the dashboard{/td}
{td}During all greenhouse operating hours, including periods when the operator is off-site and cannot physically inspect conditions{/td}
{td}Crops receive water only when needed; over- and under-watering are prevented; operator has reliable continuous data to base irrigation decisions on{/td}
{td}Highest survey score (4.83/5) and cited by 39% of respondents as their most frequent production-impacting incident — making this the single highest-priority monitored parameter. Sensor type: capacitive soil moisture sensor (per WP2.1 research). Monitoring interval: 60s per Project Charter O1. This requirement is the foundational trigger for all irrigation automation and is directly linked to GMS-16 (threshold-based auto-irrigation). Acceptance: sensor reads and transmits at ≤60s intervals; data visible on dashboard without manual refresh. Cross-references: GMS-16 (Job Story pair), GMS-24/30 (dashboard prominence requirement), GMS-26/32 (auto-stop irrigation).{/td}
{td}{status:PROPOSED|color=Yellow}{/td}
{td}Requirement analyzed and refined. Decomposed into: User = farmer, Action = continuous soil moisture monitoring at ≤60s intervals, Circumstances = all operating hours including off-site periods, Outcome = crops receive water only when needed; no over- or under-watering. Confirmed Must Have — highest survey score (4.83/5), top production incident (39%). Sensor confirmed as capacitive type. Acceptance criterion: readings update at ≤60s and are visible on dashboard without manual refresh. Linked to GMS-16 (JS pair), GMS-24/30 (dashboard prominence), GMS-26/32 (auto-stop). Moving to Proposed.{/td}
{/tr}
{tr}
{td}SHR-2{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-16}{/td}
{td}Job Story{/td}
{td}Farmer{/td}
{td}Must Have{/td}
{td}Automatically activate irrigation pump when soil moisture reading drops below the user-configured threshold{/td}
{td}When soil moisture sensor reading falls below the configured minimum threshold at any time, including off-site periods when the operator cannot physically intervene{/td}
{td}Irrigation activates automatically without on-site presence; crop moisture stress is prevented; water is applied precisely when needed without manual triggering{/td}
{td}Job Story counterpart to GMS-10 (SHR-1, already Proposed). Threshold must be user-configurable per crop type — cross-reference GMS-23/29 (crop-specific setpoints). The edge controller must execute irrigation activation locally without requiring cloud connectivity — this is a hard offline autonomy requirement critical for rural deployments with intermittent 4G. Must co-exist with auto-stop GMS-26/32: activation must halt automatically when soil reaches target moisture to prevent over-irrigation. Survey: 39% cited soil moisture drought as top production-impacting incident; automated threshold response is the core value proposition of the system. Acceptance: irrigation activates within 30s of threshold breach; activation proceeds during cloud connectivity loss; each activation event logged with timestamp, trigger value, and duration. Cross-references: GMS-10 (User Story pair), GMS-26/32 (auto-stop irrigation), GMS-23/29 (configurable thresholds), GMS-52/58 (4G/5G — offline edge autonomy required).{/td}
{td}{status:PROPOSED|color=Yellow}{/td}
{td}Requirement analyzed and refined. Decomposed into: User = farmer (off-site), Action = automatically activate irrigation on soil moisture threshold breach, Circumstances = any time soil moisture drops below configured minimum including during cloud connectivity loss, Outcome = crop stress prevention without on-site presence. Confirmed Must Have — Job Story pair to the highest-priority requirement (GMS-10, 4.83/5 survey score). Key clarification: edge controller must execute actuation locally — offline autonomy is mandatory for rural deployments. Co-existence with auto-stop (GMS-26/32) required to prevent over-watering. Threshold user-configurable per crop type (GMS-23/29). Acceptance: triggers within 30s; proceeds during cloud outage; logged with timestamp and trigger value. Moving to Proposed.{/td}
{/tr}
{tr}
{td}SHR-3{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-11}{/td}
{td}User Story{/td}
{td}Greenhouse Operator{/td}
{td}Must Have{/td}
{td}Monitor air temperature in real time and display live readings continuously on the dashboard{/td}
{td}Throughout the full day-night cycle, especially during summer overheating periods — expert interview (Bragarenco) confirmed internal greenhouse temperatures can reach 60-80°C — and during winter frost risk periods{/td}
{td}Operator detects dangerous thermal conditions early; automated heating and ventilation responses are triggered before plant stress or crop loss occurs{/td}
{td}Second highest survey score (4.61/5); 22% of respondents cited temperature extremes as a recurring production incident. Moldova's climate range (-15°C to +35°C) makes automated thermal regulation non-negotiable. Expert Bragarenco explicitly noted that motor-controlled window ventilation is essential to evacuate summer heat. Sensor: DHT22 or SHT31 — both cover temperature and humidity in a single unit, reducing hardware cost. Monitoring interval: 60s. Acceptance: continuous readings at ≤60s; heating or ventilation actuator triggered per GMS-17 when temp drops below 10°C or exceeds 35°C. Cross-references: GMS-17 (Job Story pair — automated heating/ventilation), GMS-27/33 (separate heat/frost alert types), GMS-12/18 (humidity coupling).{/td}
{td}{status:PROPOSED|color=Yellow}{/td}
{td}Requirement analyzed and refined. Decomposed into: User = greenhouse operator, Action = real-time air temperature monitoring and display, Circumstances = full day-night cycle including extreme heat and frost events, Outcome = early detection enables automated and manual response before crop damage. Confirmed Must Have — 4.61/5 survey score; 22% incident rate. Expert testimony confirms critical summer overheating risk (60-80°C internally). Sensor: DHT22/SHT31. Acceptance: continuous readings at ≤60s; actuator trigger per GMS-17 at <10°C or >35°C. Linked to GMS-17 (JS pair), GMS-27/33 (alert differentiation). Moving to Proposed.{/td}
{/tr}
{tr}
{td}SHR-4{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-17}{/td}
{td}Job Story{/td}
{td}Greenhouse Operator{/td}
{td}Must Have{/td}
{td}Automatically trigger heating actuator when temperature drops below 10°C and ventilation actuator when temperature exceeds 35°C{/td}
{td}During any hour of the full day-night operating cycle when temperature crosses either threshold — including summer peak heat events and winter frost periods in Moldova's -15°C to +35°C climate range{/td}
{td}Thermal regulation responds automatically before crop damage occurs; no manual intervention required; operator is guaranteed a safe temperature range even when off-site{/td}
{td}Job Story counterpart to GMS-11 (SHR-3, already Proposed). Two distinct actuator triggers required: heating on frost risk (<10°C) and ventilation on overheating (>35°C). Expert Bragarenco confirmed internal greenhouse temperatures can reach 60–80°C — motor-controlled window ventilation is essential to evacuate summer heat. Default thresholds (10°C/35°C) must be user-configurable per crop type (GMS-23/29). Edge controller must execute actuation locally without cloud connectivity (offline autonomy, Project Charter O5). Sensor: DHT22/SHT31 — shared hardware unit with humidity monitoring (GMS-12/18). Important coupling: ventilation triggered by high temperature (this requirement) and ventilation triggered by high humidity (GMS-18) share the same actuator — logic must be coordinated and events logged independently. Acceptance: actuator triggered within 60s of threshold breach; event logged with timestamp, trigger value, and actuator type. Cross-references: GMS-11 (User Story pair), GMS-27/33 (distinct heat/frost alert types), GMS-12/18 (humidity-ventilation coupling), GMS-23/29 (configurable setpoints).{/td}
{td}{status:PROPOSED|color=Yellow}{/td}
{td}Requirement analyzed and refined. Decomposed into: User = greenhouse operator, Action = auto-trigger heating (<10°C) or ventilation (>35°C), Circumstances = full day-night cycle including summer overheating and winter frost events, Outcome = automated thermal protection without manual intervention. Confirmed Must Have — Job Story pair to GMS-11 (4.61/5, 22% incident rate). Dual actuator logic defined: heating for frost protection, ventilation for heat evacuation. Default thresholds 10°C/35°C — user-configurable per crop (GMS-23/29). Offline autonomy required. Ventilation actuation must be coordinated with humidity-triggered ventilation (GMS-18) — same actuator, log independently. Acceptance: triggers within 60s; events logged with actuator type. Moving to Proposed.{/td}
{/tr}
{tr}
{td}SHR-5{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-12}{/td}
{td}User Story{/td}
{td}Greenhouse Operator{/td}
{td}Must Have{/td}
{td}Automatically track relative humidity at canopy level and display live readings continuously on the dashboard{/td}
{td}Continuously during all growing operations, particularly following irrigation cycles and during periods of elevated ambient humidity when fungal disease risk is highest{/td}
{td}Operator detects excessive moisture accumulation early and prevents fungal pathogen outbreaks without requiring constant manual inspection{/td}
{td}Third highest survey score (4.72/5). Excess humidity is a direct biological trigger for fungal pathogens (mold, mildew) that can destroy entire crop yields. Humidity and temperature management are tightly coupled — humidity must always be monitored in coordination with ventilation and temperature control. Sensor: DHT22/SHT31 — the same unit measures both temperature and humidity, keeping the hardware count low. Monitoring interval: 60s. Acceptance: humidity readings available at ≤60s intervals; threshold breach triggers ventilation per GMS-18. Crop-specific humidity setpoints should be user-configurable (cross-reference GMS-23/29). Cross-references: GMS-18 (Job Story pair — ventilation trigger), GMS-11/17 (temperature coupling), GMS-23/29 (crop-specific setpoints).{/td}
{td}{status:PROPOSED|color=Yellow}{/td}
{td}Requirement analyzed and refined. Decomposed into: User = greenhouse operator, Action = automatic continuous humidity tracking and display, Circumstances = all growing periods, especially post-irrigation and high-ambient-humidity events, Outcome = early fungal disease detection without manual checking. Confirmed Must Have — 4.72/5 survey score; fungal pathogens are a direct crop loss driver. Sensor confirmed as DHT22/SHT31 shared with temperature. Clarification added: humidity control must be coordinated with ventilation (GMS-18) and temperature management (GMS-17). Acceptance: readings at ≤60s; ventilation triggered per GMS-18 on breach. Linked to GMS-18 (JS pair). Moving to Proposed.{/td}
{/tr}
{tr}
{td}SHR-6{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-18}{/td}
{td}Job Story{/td}
{td}Greenhouse Operator{/td}
{td}Must Have{/td}
{td}Automatically trigger ventilation actuator when relative humidity at canopy level exceeds the user-configured safe threshold{/td}
{td}During any growing operation — particularly following irrigation cycles and during periods of elevated ambient humidity when fungal pathogen risk is highest{/td}
{td}Humidity reduced below danger threshold automatically; fungal disease outbreaks prevented; operator freed from constant manual inspection of humidity levels{/td}
{td}Job Story counterpart to GMS-12 (SHR-5, already Proposed). Critical coupling with temperature control: ventilation triggered by high humidity (this requirement) and ventilation triggered by high temperature (GMS-17) share the same vent/fan actuator — actuation logic must coordinate both conditions and log each event independently with its specific trigger type. Sensor: DHT22/SHT31 — same hardware unit shared with temperature monitoring (GMS-11/17). Humidity threshold must be crop-specific and user-configurable (GMS-23/29). Edge controller must execute actuation locally without cloud connectivity (offline autonomy, Project Charter O5). Post-irrigation surge risk: humidity typically spikes after an irrigation cycle — the ventilation trigger should be expected to activate frequently in this window and this must be accounted for in actuator wear estimates. Acceptance: ventilation triggers within 60s of exceeding threshold; event logged with timestamp, trigger value, trigger type (humidity), and duration. Cross-references: GMS-12 (User Story pair), GMS-11/17 (temperature-ventilation coupling — shared actuator), GMS-23/29 (configurable setpoints), GMS-52/58 (4G/5G — offline edge autonomy required).{/td}
{td}{status:PROPOSED|color=Yellow}{/td}
{td}Requirement analyzed and refined. Decomposed into: User = greenhouse operator, Action = auto-trigger ventilation on high-humidity threshold breach, Circumstances = all growing operations, especially post-irrigation cycles and elevated ambient humidity periods, Outcome = fungal disease prevention without constant manual monitoring. Confirmed Must Have — Job Story pair to GMS-12 (4.72/5 survey score). Key coupling identified: same ventilation actuator as GMS-17 (temperature) — logic must coordinate both triggers and log events independently with trigger type. Sensor: DHT22/SHT31 shared with temperature. Threshold user-configurable per crop (GMS-23/29). Offline autonomy required. Post-irrigation humidity surge accounted for in actuator stress analysis. Acceptance: triggers within 60s; event logged with trigger type and duration. Moving to Proposed.{/td}
{/tr}
{tr}
{td}SHR-7{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-13}{/td}
{td}User Story{/td}
{td}Greenhouse Operator{/td}
{td}Should Have{/td}
{td}Monitor CO₂ concentration levels in the greenhouse environment and display live readings on the dashboard{/td}
{td}During all growing periods when photosynthetic activity is occurring and CO₂ levels may fall below the optimal 800–1200 ppm enrichment range, particularly in sealed or poorly ventilated greenhouse conditions{/td}
{td}Operator has visibility into CO₂ conditions; suboptimal levels are detected early enabling manual or future automated enrichment to boost yield by up to 20–30%{/td}
{td}Lowest environmental survey rating (4.22/5) with zero respondents citing CO₂ as a production-impacting incident — classified as Should Have rather than Must Have because monitoring alone has limited protective value without an automated enrichment actuator (which is out of scope for the pilot). However, CO₂ enrichment in the 800–1200 ppm range is well-documented to increase crop yield by 20–30%, making monitoring the prerequisite for any future enrichment capability. Expert Bragarenco interview noted MQ-4 type gas sensors are commonly used — per WP2.1, an NDIR CO₂ sensor is recommended for precision over MQ-series resistive sensors. Monitoring interval: 60s per Project Charter O1. Acceptance: CO₂ readings at ≤60s intervals displayed on dashboard; alert generated per GMS-19 when level drops below configured threshold. Cross-references: GMS-19 (Job Story pair), GMS-14/20 (dashboard auto-refresh — CO₂ data included), GMS-15/21 (threshold alerts — applies to CO₂), GMS-23/29 (configurable CO₂ setpoint).{/td}
{td}{status:PROPOSED|color=Yellow}{/td}
{td}Requirement analyzed and refined. Decomposed into: User = greenhouse operator, Action = monitor CO₂ concentration and display on dashboard, Circumstances = all growing periods when photosynthesis is active, Outcome = early detection of suboptimal CO₂ for yield optimization. Confirmed Should Have — lowest environmental survey score (4.22/5), no production incidents cited, but enrichment (800–1200 ppm) documented to boost yield 20–30%. Sensor selection deferred to SRS (MQ-series vs NDIR). Monitoring interval: 60s per Project Charter O1. Acceptance: readings at ≤60s on dashboard; alert via GMS-19 on threshold breach. Linked to GMS-19 (JS pair). Moving to Proposed.{/td}
{/tr}
{tr}
{td}SHR-8{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-19}{/td}
{td}Job Story{/td}
{td}Greenhouse Operator{/td}
{td}Should Have{/td}
{td}Generate an alert notification when CO₂ concentration drops below the configured optimal threshold (default: 800 ppm){/td}
{td}When CO₂ levels fall below the optimal enrichment range during active growing periods, particularly in sealed or poorly ventilated greenhouse conditions where CO₂ depletion occurs due to photosynthetic consumption{/td}
{td}Operator is notified of suboptimal CO₂ conditions and can manually adjust enrichment (e.g., open CO₂ valve or adjust ventilation schedule) to improve crop productivity{/td}
{td}Job Story counterpart to GMS-13 (SHR-7, already Proposed). CO₂ depletion is a real but often unnoticed phenomenon in sealed greenhouses — plants consume CO₂ during photosynthesis, and without ventilation or enrichment, levels can drop significantly below ambient (~420 ppm). The alert function is the primary value of CO₂ monitoring in the pilot, since automated CO₂ injection is out of scope. Alert should trigger on a user-configurable threshold (default: 800 ppm per horticultural best practice). The alert must be classified as informational (in-dashboard only) per the two-tier severity model defined in GMS-15/21 and peer review R3 — CO₂ drop is not an immediate crop danger, so push/SMS escalation is not warranted. Acceptance: in-dashboard alert generated within ≤60s of CO₂ reading dropping below configured threshold; alert carries parameter name, current value, threshold value, and timestamp per GMS-21 requirements. Cross-references: GMS-13 (User Story pair), GMS-15/21 (alert framework and severity tiering), GMS-23/29 (configurable thresholds for CO₂ setpoint).{/td}
{td}{status:PROPOSED|color=Yellow}{/td}
{td}Requirement analyzed and refined. Decomposed into: User = greenhouse operator, Action = generate alert on CO₂ threshold breach, Circumstances = CO₂ depletion during active growing periods in sealed/poorly ventilated greenhouses, Outcome = operator informed to manually adjust enrichment for productivity. Confirmed Should Have — Job Story pair to GMS-13 (4.22/5 survey score, no incidents). Alert category: informational (in-dashboard only per two-tier severity model, R3), since CO₂ drop is not an immediate crop danger. Threshold user-configurable (default 800 ppm per horticultural best practice). Acceptance: alert within ≤60s of breach with full context fields per GMS-21. Linked to GMS-13 (US pair). Moving to Proposed.{/td}
{/tr}
{tr}
{td}SHR-9{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-14}{/td}
{td}User Story{/td}
{td}Greenhouse Operator{/td}
{td}Must Have{/td}
{td}Display all live sensor readings on the dashboard that refresh automatically at regular intervals without requiring manual page reload{/td}
{td}During routine daily monitoring sessions and during critical events when environmental conditions are changing rapidly and operator response time matters{/td}
{td}Operator catches emerging problems in near-real-time; no stale or outdated data is ever shown; the dashboard always accurately reflects the current greenhouse state{/td}
{td}66.7% of respondents selected the dashboard as their primary monitoring channel — auto-refresh is a prerequisite for this to be effective. Refresh interval should match the sensor read cycle (≤60s per Project Charter O1). 'Up-to-date' must be formally defined in acceptance criteria: readings must not be older than 60 seconds. A data freshness timestamp should be visible so the operator can verify the last update time. Dashboard must not require manual reload to display current values. Auto-refresh must function reliably over 4G/5G (cross-reference GMS-52/58 — high mobile latency could cause delays). Cross-references: GMS-20 (Job Story pair — rapid-change trigger), GMS-35/38 (single-page overview), GMS-52/58 (4G/5G connectivity dependency).{/td}
{td}{status:PROPOSED|color=Yellow}{/td}
{td}Requirement analyzed and refined. Decomposed into: User = greenhouse operator, Action = auto-refreshing live sensor display, Circumstances = routine checks and rapid-change events, Outcome = real-time situational awareness without manual interaction. Confirmed Must Have — 66.7% dashboard preference; stale data would defeat the purpose of real-time monitoring. Acceptance criterion: all readings refresh automatically at ≤60s; data freshness timestamp visible to operator; no manual reload required. Cross-reference added to GMS-52/58 — refresh must be reliable over 4G. Linked to GMS-20 (JS pair). Moving to Proposed.{/td}
{/tr}
{tr}
{td}SHR-10{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-20}{/td}
{td}Job Story{/td}
{td}Greenhouse Operator{/td}
{td}Must Have{/td}
{td}Dashboard refreshes all sensor data displays automatically at a fixed ≤60s interval without operator interaction, ensuring data is current during rapid environmental change events{/td}
{td}During rapid environmental change events — sudden temperature spike, post-irrigation humidity surge, moisture drop — when delayed data could cause the operator to miss a critical intervention window and crop damage occurs before action is taken{/td}
{td}Operator always sees current data during fast-moving events; response window before crop damage is maximized; no manual page reload ever required during a critical event{/td}
{td}Job Story counterpart to GMS-14 (SHR-9, already Proposed). The 'rapid change' framing elevates the urgency context: during a critical environmental event, the ≤60s auto-refresh interval (Project Charter O1) becomes a safety constraint — the operator must not miss a refresh cycle when conditions are deteriorating quickly. Implementation note: the uniform ≤60s auto-refresh defined in GMS-14 directly satisfies this requirement; no separate rapid-change detection mechanism is needed. Key addition from this Job Story: 4G/5G latency (GMS-52/58) must not silently delay the refresh cycle — a data freshness timestamp must always be visible to indicate the last successful data reception time. If a refresh cycle is delayed beyond ≤60s, a visual warning must be shown. Acceptance: all sensor data refreshed at ≤60s intervals; data freshness timestamp always visible; visual warning displayed if data is older than 60s; no manual reload required. Cross-references: GMS-14 (User Story pair), GMS-35/38 (single-page dashboard overview — where refresh is visible), GMS-52/58 (4G latency must not silently delay refresh cycle).{/td}
{td}{status:PROPOSED|color=Yellow}{/td}
{td}Requirement analyzed and refined. Decomposed into: User = greenhouse operator, Action = dashboard auto-refresh at ≤60s during rapid environmental change, Circumstances = fast-changing critical events where delayed data means missed intervention window, Outcome = maximized response time through always-current data display. Confirmed Must Have — Job Story pair to GMS-14 (66.7% dashboard preference). Key clarification: ≤60s auto-refresh from GMS-14 directly satisfies this — the Job Story context emphasizes this interval becomes a safety constraint during critical events. 4G latency (GMS-52/58) must not silently delay refresh — data freshness timestamp and staleness warning required. Acceptance: data ≤60s old always; freshness timestamp visible; visual warning if stale. Moving to Proposed.{/td}
{/tr}
{tr}
{td}SHR-11{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-15}{/td}
{td}User Story{/td}
{td}Farmer{/td}
{td}Must Have{/td}
{td}Generate and display an in-system warning alert whenever any monitored environmental parameter exceeds a configured safe operating threshold{/td}
{td}At any time a threshold is breached, including during unattended periods when the operator is not actively viewing the dashboard or is off-site{/td}
{td}Operator is notified of dangerous conditions before plant stress or crop loss occurs; monitoring coverage is maintained even without on-site presence{/td}
{td}Survey respondents explicitly requested threshold-based alerts across all monitored parameters — without in-system alerting, real-time data has no protective value during unattended periods. A two-tier severity model is strongly recommended per peer review R3 (WP4.2): informational events (minor deviations) should appear in-dashboard only; critical events (e.g., temp >35°C, soil moisture <10%, actuator failure) should escalate to push/SMS via GMS-41. The team must formally define the critical event list in the SRS acceptance criteria phase. Alert fatigue is a real risk if all events trigger push notifications — tiering is essential to user adoption. In-dashboard alert must appear within one data cycle (≤60s) of the threshold breach. Cross-references: GMS-21 (Job Story pair), GMS-40/41 (push/SMS notification layer), GMS-17/18/16 (automated actuator responses).{/td}
{td}{status:PROPOSED|color=Yellow}{/td}
{td}Requirement analyzed and refined. Decomposed into: User = farmer, Action = in-system warning alert triggered on parameter threshold breach, Circumstances = any threshold breach including during unattended/off-site periods, Outcome = operator alerted before crop damage occurs. Confirmed Must Have — alerting is the essential protective layer for unattended greenhouse periods. Two-tier severity model flagged per peer review R3: informational (in-dashboard) vs critical (push/SMS per GMS-41). Team must formally define critical event list in SRS acceptance criteria. Acceptance: in-dashboard alert appears within ≤60s of breach. Linked to GMS-21 (JS pair), GMS-40/41 (notifications). Moving to Proposed.{/td}
{/tr}
{tr}
{td}SHR-12{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-21}{/td}
{td}Job Story{/td}
{td}Farmer{/td}
{td}Must Have{/td}
{td}Generate and display an immediate in-dashboard alert notification when any monitored parameter crosses a configured threshold, carrying parameter name, current value, threshold value, and timestamp{/td}
{td}At the moment any threshold is breached — including during unattended periods when the operator is not actively viewing the dashboard and would not otherwise see the raw data crossing the limit{/td}
{td}Operator can intervene before plant stress or crop loss occurs even when not actively monitoring; protective coverage maintained during all unattended greenhouse periods{/td}
{td}Job Story counterpart to GMS-15 (SHR-11, already Proposed). 'Immediate' formally defined: alert must appear within one sensor read cycle (≤60s) of the threshold breach — same cadence as the monitoring interval. Each alert must carry: parameter name, current value, threshold value, and timestamp of breach to give actionable context. Two-tier severity model confirmed per peer review R3 (WP4.2): informational events (minor or first-cycle deviations) appear in-dashboard only; critical events (temp >35°C, soil moisture <10%, actuator failure, connectivity loss) escalate to push/SMS per GMS-40/41. The formal critical event list must be defined in SRS acceptance criteria to prevent alert fatigue — if every event triggers push notifications, operators will disable alerts. Acceptance: in-dashboard alert appears within ≤60s of breach; alert carries all four required data fields; severity tier correctly routes event. Cross-references: GMS-15 (User Story pair), GMS-40/41 (push/SMS escalation layer), GMS-16/17/18 (automated actuator responses triggered by same threshold events), GMS-23/29 (configurable thresholds that define breach conditions).{/td}
{td}{status:PROPOSED|color=Yellow}{/td}
{td}Requirement analyzed and refined. Decomposed into: User = farmer, Action = immediate in-dashboard alert on parameter threshold breach with full context data, Circumstances = any breach including unattended/off-site periods when operator is not watching the dashboard, Outcome = intervention capability before crop damage even without active monitoring. Confirmed Must Have — Job Story pair to GMS-15 (alerting is the essential protection layer for unattended periods). Formal alert content defined: parameter name, current value, threshold value, timestamp. Two-tier severity model confirmed per peer review R3: informational = in-dashboard; critical = escalate to push/SMS (GMS-40/41). Critical event list must be formally defined in SRS to prevent alert fatigue. Acceptance: alert within ≤60s with all four fields; severity routing correct. Moving to Proposed.{/td}
{/tr}
{tr}
{td}SHR-13{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-22}{/td}
{td}User Story{/td}
{td}Farmer{/td}
{td}Must Have{/td}
{td}Configure time-based irrigation schedules (start time, duration, frequency) that execute autonomously without requiring sensor input, cloud connectivity, or on-site presence{/td}
{td}When the farmer is absent from the greenhouse for an extended period — ranging from days to several months — or when sensor-based control is temporarily unavailable due to hardware failure or connectivity loss{/td}
{td}Irrigation continues on a predictable schedule regardless of absence duration or connectivity status; crops are maintained autonomously; the greenhouse remains fully operational without anyone on-site{/td}
{td}From WP4.2: one survey respondent required fully autonomous operation for up to 3 months while abroad; schedule-based irrigation ensures continuity when connectivity or sensor feedback is unavailable — this is the fallback mechanism when real-time sensor control (GMS-16) is unavailable. Critical requirement: timed schedule must co-exist with and not conflict with threshold-based sensor-triggered irrigation (GMS-16). Conflict resolution rule: a scheduled irrigation run should be automatically skipped or aborted if soil moisture is already at or above the target setpoint at execution time — this prevents over-watering when the soil is already wet. The edge controller must store and execute schedules locally without requiring cloud connection — hard offline autonomy requirement per Project Charter O5 (72h offline minimum; the 3-month use case requires indefinite offline schedule execution). Schedule management UI must support: create, edit, delete, and view upcoming scheduled runs from dashboard. Schedule execution events must be logged with timestamp, planned time, actual start time, and skip reason (if skipped). Acceptance: scheduled irrigation runs at configured time during cloud outage; skips if soil already at or above setpoint; operator can fully manage schedules from dashboard; execution logged. Cross-references: GMS-28 (Job Story pair, SHR-14), GMS-16 (sensor-triggered control — co-existence required), GMS-26/32 (auto-stop applies to scheduled runs too), GMS-23/29 (configurable setpoints used for skip-if-wet logic).{/td}
{td}{status:PROPOSED|color=Yellow}{/td}
{td}Requirement analyzed and refined. Decomposed into: User = farmer absent for extended periods (days to months), Action = configure and execute autonomous timed irrigation schedules, Circumstances = extended absence or sensor/connectivity failure making real-time control unavailable, Outcome = crops maintained autonomously without on-site presence. Confirmed Must Have — survey evidence of 3-month autonomous operation requirement; also serves as fallback when GMS-16 sensor-based control is unavailable. Key clarifications: (1) schedule must not conflict with sensor-triggered control — skip if soil already at setpoint (prevents over-watering); (2) edge controller executes schedules locally without cloud (Project Charter O5); (3) auto-stop (GMS-26/32) still applies during scheduled runs. Full schedule management (create/edit/delete) from dashboard required; execution events logged. Linked to GMS-28 (JS pair, SHR-14). Moving to Proposed.{/td}
{/tr}
{tr}
{td}SHR-14{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-28}{/td}
{td}Job Story{/td}
{td}Farmer (abroad){/td}
{td}Must Have{/td}
{td}Execute pre-configured timed irrigation schedules (start time, duration, frequency) autonomously without requiring sensor input, cloud connectivity, or operator presence{/td}
{td}When the farmer is abroad for extended periods (days to months) and cannot physically intervene, or when sensor-based control (GMS-16) is temporarily unavailable due to hardware failure, sensor calibration drift, or connectivity loss{/td}
{td}Greenhouse irrigation continues on a reliable schedule regardless of farmer absence, connectivity status, or sensor availability; crops are sustained autonomously for the full absence period{/td}
{td}Job Story counterpart to GMS-22 (SHR-13, already Proposed). One survey respondent explicitly required fully autonomous operation for up to 3 months while abroad — this is the flagship absence use case. The edge controller must store and execute schedules locally without cloud connection — hard offline autonomy requirement per Project Charter O5 (72h minimum; this use case demands indefinite offline schedule execution). Critical co-existence rule with sensor-triggered irrigation (GMS-16): a scheduled irrigation run must be automatically skipped or aborted if soil moisture is already at or above the target setpoint — this prevents over-watering when the soil is already wet (cross-reference GMS-26/32 auto-stop). Expert Bragarenco described operational rules: '0.5 liters in the morning, 1 liter at noon, 2 liters in the evening' — confirming the real-world need for configurable time-based irrigation profiles. Schedule management UI must support: create, edit, delete, and view upcoming scheduled runs from dashboard. Each schedule execution event must be logged with: timestamp, planned time, actual start time, duration, and skip reason (if skipped due to adequate soil moisture). Acceptance: scheduled irrigation runs at configured time during cloud outage; skipped if soil already at or above setpoint; full CRUD from dashboard; execution logged with all required fields. Cross-references: GMS-22 (User Story pair, SHR-13), GMS-16 (sensor-triggered control — co-existence and conflict resolution required), GMS-26/32 (auto-stop applies to scheduled runs too), GMS-23/29 (configurable setpoints used for skip-if-wet logic).{/td}
{td}{status:PROPOSED|color=Yellow}{/td}
{td}Requirement analyzed and refined. Decomposed into: User = farmer abroad for extended periods, Action = execute autonomous timed irrigation schedules without sensor or cloud dependency, Circumstances = extended absence (days to months) or sensor unavailability, Outcome = crops sustained autonomously for the full absence period. Confirmed Must Have — Job Story pair to GMS-22 (survey evidence: 3-month autonomous operation; fallback when GMS-16 sensor control unavailable). Key clarifications: (1) schedule co-exists with sensor-triggered control — skip if soil already at setpoint (prevents over-watering); (2) edge controller executes locally without cloud (Project Charter O5 — indefinite offline required for this use case); (3) auto-stop (GMS-26/32) still applies during scheduled runs. Expert Bragarenco confirmed time-based irrigation profiles as real operational need. Full CRUD from dashboard required; execution events logged. Linked to GMS-22 (US pair, SHR-13). Moving to Proposed.{/td}
{/tr}
{tr}
{td}SHR-15{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-23}{/td}
{td}User Story{/td}
{td}Farmer{/td}
{td}Must Have{/td}
{td}Configure custom acceptable operating ranges (setpoints) for temperature and humidity parameters through the dashboard, defining crop-specific comfort zones that trigger automated system responses when breached{/td}
{td}When the farmer grows different crop types with distinct environmental needs, or when switching between crops between growing seasons, requiring the system to adapt its automated response thresholds accordingly{/td}
{td}The automation system responds according to specific crop requirements rather than fixed factory defaults; the system is applicable across varied growing scenarios with different crops and seasonal conditions{/td}
{td}This is the foundational configurability requirement — without user-configurable setpoints, all automation responses (irrigation GMS-16, heating/ventilation GMS-17, humidity ventilation GMS-18) would be locked to fixed factory defaults, making the system unusable for operators growing different crop types. Crop temperature comfort zones vary significantly: tomatoes (18–27°C), lettuce (15–20°C), peppers (21–30°C). Humidity ranges similarly vary by species. Expert Bragarenco interview confirmed threshold-based control: 'there are threshold systems where you set the acceptable range and the system operates within it.' The UI must allow per-parameter threshold configuration with clearly defined min/max/target values. Configuration changes must be stored on the edge controller and persist through power cycles and connectivity loss (offline autonomy requirement, Project Charter O5). A crop-presets feature (pre-loaded profiles for common crops like tomatoes, peppers, lettuce) is recommended but not required for the pilot — Could Have enhancement. Acceptance criteria: operator can set custom min/max thresholds for temperature and humidity via dashboard; thresholds persist on edge controller; actuator responses (GMS-17/18) use the configured thresholds. Cross-references: GMS-29 (Job Story pair — reconfiguration context), GMS-16/17/18 (all automated responses depend on these configurable thresholds), GMS-22/28 (schedule skip logic uses setpoints), GMS-26/32 (auto-stop uses soil moisture setpoint).{/td}
{td}{status:PROPOSED|color=Yellow}{/td}
{td}Requirement analyzed and refined. Decomposed into: User = farmer growing varied crop types, Action = configure custom temperature and humidity setpoints via dashboard, Circumstances = different crops with distinct environmental needs or season transitions, Outcome = automation adapts to specific crop requirements instead of fixed defaults. Confirmed Must Have — without configurable setpoints, all automation (GMS-16/17/18) is locked to factory defaults making the system unusable for varied crops. Crop ranges cited: tomatoes 18–27°C, lettuce 15–20°C, peppers 21–30°C. Expert Bragarenco confirmed threshold-based operational model. Configurations must persist on edge controller through power cycles and connectivity loss. Crop-presets feature flagged as Could Have enhancement. Acceptance: custom min/max thresholds configurable via dashboard; persist on edge; actuator responses use configured values. Linked to GMS-29 (JS pair). Moving to Proposed.{/td}
{/tr}
{tr}
{td}SHR-16{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-29}{/td}
{td}Job Story{/td}
{td}Farmer{/td}
{td}Must Have{/td}
{td}Reconfigure temperature and humidity operating ranges through the dashboard when transitioning between different crop types, with the new setpoints taking effect on all automated system responses immediately{/td}
{td}When the farmer switches to a different crop between growing seasons or within the same season, and the new crop has distinct environmental requirements that differ from the currently configured thresholds{/td}
{td}The automated system seamlessly adapts to the new crop's environmental needs; the farmer does not need to manually monitor or override the system after reconfiguration; transition between crops does not require any hardware changes{/td}
{td}Job Story counterpart to GMS-23 (SHR-15, already Proposed). This requirement formalizes the crop-transition scenario — the most common real-world use case for threshold reconfiguration. Moldovan greenhouses frequently rotate between tomatoes, peppers, cucumbers, and lettuce across seasons, each with distinct temperature and humidity needs. When new setpoints are saved, all dependent automated responses (heating GMS-17, ventilation GMS-17/18, irrigation GMS-16) must immediately use the updated values — there must be no stale-setpoint delay. The reconfiguration must propagate to the edge controller and take effect locally even without cloud connectivity — this is a subset of the offline autonomy requirement. Important: the dashboard should clearly show the currently active setpoints and confirm successful application to the edge controller. A setpoint change history log is recommended for traceability (e.g., 'temperature range changed from 18–27°C to 15–20°C at timestamp by operator'). Acceptance: setpoints reconfigurable from dashboard; changes take effect within one control loop cycle (≤60s); edge controller adopts new values even during cloud outage; dashboard confirms active setpoints after change. Cross-references: GMS-23 (User Story pair, SHR-15), GMS-16/17/18 (dependent automated responses), GMS-22/28 (schedule skip logic — uses setpoints).{/td}
{td}{status:PROPOSED|color=Yellow}{/td}
{td}Requirement analyzed and refined. Decomposed into: User = farmer switching crops, Action = reconfigure temperature/humidity setpoints via dashboard, Circumstances = crop transition requiring different environmental thresholds, Outcome = seamless automation adaptation to new crop needs without hardware changes. Confirmed Must Have — Job Story pair to GMS-23. Moldovan greenhouses rotate between tomatoes, peppers, cucumbers, lettuce with distinct needs. Key clarification: new setpoints must propagate to edge controller and take effect within one control cycle (≤60s) including during cloud outage. Dashboard must confirm active setpoints. Setpoint change history log recommended for traceability. Acceptance: setpoints reconfigurable from dashboard; effect within ≤60s; edge adopts during cloud outage; confirmation displayed. Linked to GMS-23 (US pair, SHR-15). Moving to Proposed.{/td}
{/tr}
{tr}
{td}SHR-17{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-34}{/td}
{td}User Story{/td}
{td}Greenhouse Owner{/td}
{td}Must Have{/td}
{td}Access the full GMS dashboard from any standard web browser without installing an app{/td}
{td}When travelling or working remotely using any available device (laptop, tablet, phone){/td}
{td}Monitoring is accessible from any device; no hardware or app lock-in; adoption barrier is reduced{/td}
{td}66.7% of survey respondents selected the browser dashboard as their preferred monitoring channel. Zero-install browser access is essential for non-technical users. Acceptance: dashboard fully functional on Chrome, Firefox, and Safari on both desktop and mobile. Must be combined with mobile-responsive design (GMS-36) — browser access alone is insufficient if the layout breaks on small screens. Cross-reference: GMS-52/58 (4G/5G connectivity). Linked to GMS-37 (Job Story pair).{/td}
{td}{status:PROPOSED|color=Yellow}{/td}
{td}Requirement analyzed and refined. Decomposed into: User = greenhouse owner, Action = access dashboard from any browser with no app install, Circumstances = remote or travelling with any device, Outcome = no device/app lock-in. Clarification added: browser access must be paired with mobile-responsive design (GMS-36) to be meaningful — these two requirements are interdependent. Acceptance: fully functional on Chrome, Firefox, Safari on desktop and mobile. Cross-reference added to GMS-52/58 for connectivity dependency. Linked to GMS-37. Moving to Proposed.{/td}
{/tr}
{tr}
{td}SHR-18{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-37}{/td}
{td}Job Story{/td}
{td}Greenhouse Owner{/td}
{td}Must Have{/td}
{td}Access dashboard remotely via any standard web browser without app installation{/td}
