{tr}
{td}SHR-20{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-38}{/td}
{td}Job Story{/td}
{td}Greenhouse Operator{/td}
{td}Must Have{/td}
{td}View all critical greenhouse conditions on one consolidated page without navigating{/td}
{td}During quick status checks, possibly under time pressure or while doing other tasks{/td}
{td}All critical parameters visible on a single screen; no additional navigation required{/td}
{td}Job Story pair to GMS-35 (US). 'Critical conditions' must be explicitly listed in acceptance criteria: soil moisture, temperature, humidity, CO2 levels, actuator status, and active alerts. 'At a glance' implies data must be visually prioritized - consider using color-coded status indicators. Page load time should be defined (e.g., <3s on 4G).{/td}
{td}{status:PROPOSED|color=Yellow}{/td}
{td}Analyzed: operator doing quick check, action is viewing single-page overview, circumstance is time-constrained situation, outcome is instant situational awareness. Clarification added on what 'critical conditions' includes.
Moving to Proposed.{/td}
{/tr}
{tr}
{td}SHR-21{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-40}{/td}
{td}User Story{/td}
{td}Farmer{/td}
{td}Should Have{/td}
{td}Deliver push notifications or SMS alerts to the operator's mobile phone when a critical threshold is exceeded or a system malfunction is detected{/td}
{td}When the operator is not on-site and cannot view the in-dashboard alert — particularly during off-hours, nighttime, or extended absences when the dashboard is not actively displayed{/td}
{td}Operator is immediately made aware of dangerous conditions regardless of their physical location or current activity; response time is minimized even when not actively monitoring the dashboard{/td}
{td}27.8% of survey respondents preferred SMS/push as their primary alert channel — however, in-dashboard alerts (GMS-15/21) cover the baseline need, which is why this is classified as Should Have rather than Must Have. Expert Bragarenco confirmed alerts are 'obligatory' as a concept but did not specify a channel. The two-tier severity model defined in peer review R3 (WP4.2) applies directly: this requirement implements the escalation layer — only critical events (temperature >35°C, soil moisture <10%, actuator failure, connectivity loss) should trigger push/SMS to avoid alert fatigue. Informational events (minor deviations, first-cycle threshold touches) remain in-dashboard only per GMS-15/21. The critical event list must be formally defined in the SRS acceptance criteria phase. Implementation options: Firebase Cloud Messaging (FCM) for push notifications (requires service worker in the web app — compatible with PWA approach); SMS via Twilio or local GSM module. SMS has the advantage of working without smartphone internet (relevant for the 11.1% of survey respondents with no stable connection). For pilot: push notification via web browser (FCM) is the recommended minimum; SMS integration can be deferred to post-pilot. Acceptance: push notification received on operator’s phone within 60s of critical threshold breach; notification includes parameter name, value, and severity; operator can configure which events trigger phone notification. Cross-references: GMS-41 (Job Story pair, SHR-22 — already Proposed), GMS-15/21 (in-dashboard alert baseline — this is the escalation layer), GMS-17/18/16 (actuator events that could trigger notifications).{/td}
{td}{status:PROPOSED|color=Yellow}{/td}
{td}Requirement analyzed and refined. Decomposed into: User = farmer away from dashboard, Action = receive push/SMS notification on phone for critical events, Circumstances = off-site periods when dashboard is not visible, Outcome = immediate awareness of dangerous conditions regardless of location. Confirmed Should Have — 27.8% preferred SMS/push; in-dashboard alerts cover baseline (GMS-15/21). Expert Bragarenco confirmed alerts as obligatory. Two-tier severity model per peer review R3: only critical events (temp >35°C, moisture <10%, actuator failure) escalate to phone notification. Critical event list to be formally defined in SRS. Pilot recommendation: web push via FCM as minimum; SMS deferred to post-pilot. Acceptance: notification within 60s of critical breach; includes parameter, value, severity. Linked to GMS-41 (JS pair, SHR-22 — already Proposed). Moving to Proposed.{/td}
{/tr}
{tr}
{td}SHR-22{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-41}{/td}
{td}Job Story{/td}
{td}Farmer / Greenhouse Operator{/td}
{td}Should Have{/td}
{td}Receive push notification on mobile device when any sensor reading exceeds a critical threshold{/td}
{td}When operator is not on-site and cannot see the in-dashboard alert; critical event (e.g., extreme temperature, actuator failure){/td}
{td}Operator is immediately alerted regardless of location and can react before crop damage occurs{/td}
{td}Job Story pair to GMS-40 (US). Classification as Should Have is correct, in-dashboard alerts cover the baseline. Two-tier severity model recommended (per peer review R3): informational = in-dashboard only; critical = push/SMS triggered. Team must define which events qualify as 'critical' (e.g., temp > 35°C, soil moisture < 10%, actuator failure). Alert fatigue risk if severity not tiered.{/td}
{td}{status:PROPOSED|color=Yellow}{/td}
{td}Analyzed: off-site farmer, action is receiving push notification, circumstance is away-from-site during threshold breach, outcome is immediate reaction capability. Severity tiering noted per peer review R3. Moving to Proposed.{/td}
{/tr}
{tr}
{td}SHR-23{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-42}{/td}
{td}User Story{/td}
{td}Greenhouse Operator / Business Owner{/td}
{td}Should Have{/td}
{td}View historical environmental trend data with visualizations over configurable time periods{/td}
