{tr}
{td}SHR-29{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-54}{/td}
{td}User Story{/td}
{td}Investor / Business Owner{/td}
{td}Shoud Have{/td}
{td}Access measurable, comparative data showing proven reductions in water and energy operational costs achieved by the GMS versus a manually-established baseline{/td}
{td}When reviewing pilot operational results at the end of a growing period to evaluate financial return before committing further investment funds or scaling the system{/td}
{td}Investor has quantified, evidence-based ROI data enabling informed funding and scaling decisions{/td}
{td}Research confirms smart greenhouse systems can achieve up to 40% water and 25% energy savings (Project Charter references). However, actual savings figures are a pilot-phase outcome — the logging infrastructure must be built and operational first, and the pilot must run for a sufficient period. Per peer review R1 (WP4.2), a concrete measurement mechanism must be defined: system logs water and energy consumption and compares it against a manually-set baseline established at pilot start. Per peer review R2, 90-day minimum retention is required to show meaningful seasonal trends. Hard dependency: the historical data module (GMS-42/49) and the consumption logging capability (GMS-56/SHR-30) must both be in place before this requirement can be validated. This requirement covers what the investor needs to see; the logging and comparison mechanism is defined in GMS-56. Acceptance: dashboard provides a comparative view of GMS-managed consumption vs manual baseline, with percentage savings calculated. Cross-references: GMS-56 (Job Story pair, SHR-30), GMS-42/49 (historical data module — prerequisite), GMS-53/55 (affordability requirements){/td}
{td}{status:PROPOSED|color=Yellow}{/td}
{td}Requirement analyzed and refined. Decomposed into: User = investor/business owner, Action = view proven operational cost reduction data compared to manual baseline, Circumstances = end-of-pilot review for investment evaluation, Outcome = quantified ROI evidence enabling informed funding decisions. Classified as Should Have — demonstrating savings validates ROI but requires completed pilot operational data and cannot be verified before pilot end. Peer review R1: baseline must be manually set at pilot start for meaningful comparison. Peer review R2: 90-day minimum retention required. Critical dependency: historical data module (GMS-42/49) and consumption logging (GMS-56) must be operational first. Acceptance: comparative consumption dashboard showing GMS vs manual baseline with calculated percentage savings. Linked to GMS-56 (JS pair, SHR-30). Moving to Proposed.{/td}
{/tr}
{tr}
{td}SHR-30{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-56}{/td}
{td}Job Story{/td}
{td}Investor / Business Owner{/td}
{td}Should Have{/td}
{td}Log and display water and energy consumption data comparable to a manually established baseline{/td}
{td}When reviewing pilot operational results at the end of a growing period{/td}
{td}Investor can quantify savings against baseline and calculate ROI; evidence-based funding decisions are enabled{/td}
{td}Research confirms smart greenhouse systems can achieve up to 40% water and 25% energy savings. Acceptance: system logs consumption data and allows comparison to a baseline set at pilot start (per peer review R1). Requires 90-day data retention (per peer review R2) to show meaningful trends across a full growing cycle. Depends on historical data module (GMS-42/49) being in place. Actual savings figures are a pilot-phase outcome — the logging infrastructure must be built during the implementation phase. Linked to GMS-54 (User Story pair).{/td}
{td}{status:PROPOSED|color=Yellow}{/td}
{td}Requirement analyzed and refined. Decomposed into: User = investor/business owner, Action = log and display water and energy consumption vs. baseline, Circumstances = end-of-period pilot review, Outcome = quantified ROI evidence. Peer review R1: baseline must be manually set at pilot start for meaningful comparison. Peer review R2: 90-day minimum retention required for seasonal trend analysis. Dependency: historical data module (GMS-42/49) must be in place before this can be validated. Linked to GMS-54. Moving to Proposed.{/td}
{/tr}
{tr}
{td}SHR-31{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-45}{/td}
{td}User Story{/td}
{td}Large Agricultural Enterprise Manager{/td}
{td}Won't Have{/td}
{td}Access a unified dashboard that aggregates monitoring, alerts, and control for multiple greenhouse sites and zones from a single interface{/td}
{td}When managing a multi-site agricultural enterprise and needing to review operational status and control all locations without physically visiting each site{/td}
{td}Centralized operations management for multiple locations; under-performing sites identified and targeted without physical visits; resource allocation optimized across the enterprise{/td}
{td}WP4.2 classification: Won't Have for the current pilot. Rationale: majority of surveyed operators manage a single greenhouse; multi-site architecture would add significant infrastructure and development complexity — multi-tenant data isolation, per-site sensor discovery, cross-site aggregation — that is out of scope for the pilot deployment. Post-pilot roadmap consideration: the system architecture must not create permanent barriers to future multi-site extension. Design guidance for SRS: data schemas should include a site/zone identifier field; device identity and MQTT topic structure should be designed with tenancy separation in mind to allow future multi-site support without a full architectural rewrite. No pilot acceptance criteria required for this requirement. Cross-reference: GMS-46 (Job Story pair, SHR-32).{/td}
{td}{status:PROPOSED|color=Yellow}{/td}
{td}Requirement analyzed. Decomposed into: User = large enterprise manager with multiple greenhouse sites, Action = access unified multi-site dashboard for monitoring and control, Circumstances = remote multi-site operations without physical visits, Outcome = centralized operational oversight and resource optimization. Confirmed Won't Have per WP4.2 MoSCoW analysis — pilot targets single-greenhouse operators; multi-site adds significant complexity. Architecture note recorded: system design should not permanently block future multi-site extension — site/zone identifier in data schemas recommended. No pilot acceptance criteria. Linked to GMS-46 (JS pair, SHR-32). Moving to Proposed (analysis and Won't Have classification recorded).{/td}
{/tr}
{tr}
{td}SHR-32{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-46}{/td}
{td}Job Story{/td}
{td}Large Agricultural Enterprise Manager{/td}
{td}Won't Have{/td}
{td}Compare environmental parameter data (soil moisture, temperature, humidity, CO₂, light intensity) across multiple greenhouse zones or sites via the dashboard{/td}
{td}When an enterprise manager is reviewing multi-zone performance to identify productivity differences between sites and reallocate resources or operational focus accordingly{/td}
{td}Under-performing zones are identified based on actual environmental data; resources and agronomic attention are allocated to where they are most needed{/td}
{td}Job Story counterpart to GMS-45 (SHR-31, Won't Have). Won't Have for the same reasons as GMS-45: pilot targets single-greenhouse operators and multi-site data comparison requires significant additional architecture — cross-site data aggregation, unified time-series storage, and a comparative visualization layer. The scope of what 'compare' means must be defined before implementation: point-in-time side-by-side vs historical trend comparison vs anomaly detection across sites — these represent very different implementation complexity levels. Post-pilot: if multi-site is added, this requirement defines the core use case for the comparative analytics feature. Architecture note: time-series data schema must support a site/zone key to enable future cross-site queries without schema migration. Cross-references: GMS-45 (User Story pair, SHR-31).{/td}
{td}{status:PROPOSED|color=Yellow}{/td}
{td}Requirement analyzed. Decomposed into: User = large enterprise manager, Action = compare environmental data across multiple greenhouse zones/sites, Circumstances = multi-site performance review for resource reallocation, Outcome = evidence-based identification of under-performing zones. Confirmed Won't Have — Job Story pair to GMS-45 (SHR-31); same rationale (pilot scope, single-greenhouse focus). Post-pilot scope note added: 'compare' must be defined before implementation (point-in-time vs historical vs anomaly). Architecture note: time-series schema should include site/zone key for future extensibility. Linked to GMS-45 (US pair, SHR-31). Moving to Proposed (analysis and Won't Have classification recorded).{/td}
{/tr}
{tr}
{td}SHR-33{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-47}{/td}
{td}User Story{/td}
{td}System Administrator{/td}
{td}Should Have{/td}
{td}Implement TLS 1.2+ encryption for all cloud communications, X.509 certificate authentication for device identity, and role-based access control (RBAC) for all dashboard and actuator operations{/td}
{td}Whenever the greenhouse edge controller communicates with the cloud platform, and whenever any user authenticates and interacts with the dashboard to view data or trigger actuator controls{/td}
{td}Unauthorized parties cannot intercept sensor data or manipulate physical actuators over public networks; system integrity and physical safety are maintained across all remote access scenarios{/td}
{td}WP4.2 classification: Should Have for pilot. Critical security context: the GMS controls physical actuators (irrigation pumps, heaters, ventilation motors) over a public internet connection — unauthorized access is not just a data confidentiality risk but a physical safety and crop safety risk. OWASP Top 10 implications: broken access control and identification/authentication failures are directly applicable. Specific requirements: (1) MQTT broker must enforce TLS 1.2+ for all device-to-cloud communication — no unencrypted connections permitted; (2) each edge controller device must have a unique X.509 certificate provisioned at deployment — no shared credentials; (3) dashboard must be served over HTTPS only — no HTTP fallback; (4) RBAC minimum: two roles required — Operator role (full dashboard access including actuator triggers) and Observer role (read-only sensor data and alert view, no actuator access); (5) all authentication events must be logged. Should Have classification reflects that no external users access the system during the pilot phase — however, TLS and device certificates should be provisioned before any cloud deployment to avoid retrofitting security onto a deployed system. Acceptance: all communications TLS 1.2+; device identity via X.509; dashboard HTTPS only; RBAC enforced with at least two roles; authentication events logged. Cross-references: GMS-48 (Job Story pair, SHR-34), GMS-31 (remote irrigation trigger — must be authenticated), GMS-52/58 (connectivity — authentication must function reliably over 4G).{/td}
{td}{status:PROPOSED|color=Yellow}{/td}
{td}Requirement analyzed and refined. Decomposed into: User = system administrator, Action = implement TLS encryption, X.509 device authentication, and RBAC, Circumstances = all cloud communication and dashboard access scenarios, Outcome = unauthorized access and manipulation of physical actuators prevented. Confirmed Should Have for pilot — no external users during pilot, but security must be provisioned before cloud deployment to avoid retrofitting. OWASP relevance noted (broken access control, authentication failures). Specific security requirements defined: TLS 1.2+ for MQTT; unique X.509 per device; HTTPS-only dashboard; minimum two RBAC roles (Operator/Observer). Physical actuator control risk elevates urgency vs typical data-only web apps. Authentication events must be logged. Linked to GMS-48 (JS pair, SHR-34). Moving to Proposed.{/td}
{/tr}
{tr}
{td}SHR-34{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-48}{/td}
{td}Job Story{/td}
{td}System Administrator{/td}
{td}Should Have{/td}
{td}Authenticate every greenhouse edge controller to the cloud platform using device-specific X.509 certificates and authenticate every dashboard user session with validated credentials before granting any access{/td}
{td}During every connection event between an edge controller and the cloud, and at the start of every user session on the dashboard — especially critical when remote actuator control is being accessed{/td}
{td}Only authorized, identified devices and users can connect to the system; remote actuator control is protected from unauthorized access; unauthorized irrigation, heating, or ventilation cannot be triggered remotely{/td}
{td}Job Story counterpart to GMS-47 (SHR-33, already Proposed). Specific actuator threat model: unauthorized irrigation activation could over-water and damage root systems; unauthorized heating could overheat the greenhouse; unauthorized ventilation during frost could expose crops to temperature extremes. These are physical crop safety risks, not just data breaches. Device identity requirements: each edge controller must have a unique X.509 certificate provisioned at deployment; shared device secrets are not acceptable for production; certificate rotation procedure must be defined in the deployment documentation. Dashboard session requirements: minimum username + password authentication over HTTPS; session tokens must have defined expiry (recommended: 24h for regular sessions, 1h for sessions with actuator access); no persistent anonymous sessions permitted. Per Project Charter security objectives, secure authentication must be in place before any production cloud deployment. 4G reliability note: authentication handshake (TLS and certificate exchange) must complete reliably under 4G latency conditions — cross-reference GMS-52/58. Should Have for pilot (no external users during pilot but provisioned before cloud deployment). Acceptance: each device connects with unique X.509 certificate; all dashboard sessions authenticated with expiring tokens; no anonymous access; actuator endpoints require valid authenticated session. Cross-references: GMS-47 (User Story pair, SHR-33), GMS-31/25 (remote irrigation/manual control — depends on authenticated session), GMS-52/58 (connectivity — auth handshake must work over 4G).{/td}
{td}{status:PROPOSED|color=Yellow}{/td}
{td}Requirement analyzed and refined. Decomposed into: User = system administrator / greenhouse owner, Action = authenticate edge controller with X.509 certificates and authenticate every dashboard session with expiring credentials, Circumstances = every device connection and every user login, especially when remote actuator control is involved, Outcome = only authorized devices and users can connect; physical actuator control protected from unauthorized remote access. Confirmed Should Have — Job Story pair to GMS-47 (SRS-33). Actuator-specific threat model documented: unauthorized irrigation/heating/ventilation are physical crop safety risks. Device identity: unique X.509 per controller; no shared credentials. Session management: expiring tokens required; no anonymous sessions; actuator endpoints demand valid session. Auth handshake must be reliable over 4G (GMS-52/58). Linked to GMS-47 (US pair, SHR-33). Moving to Proposed.{/td}
{/tr}
{tr}
{td}SHR-35{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-24}{/td}
{td}User Story{/td}
{td}Farmer{/td}
{td}Must Have{/td}
{td}Display soil moisture reading as the primary, top-priority widget on the dashboard, positioned above all other parameters on initial page load{/td}
{td}When the farmer opens or navigates to the dashboard at any time — during routine daily checks, emergency assessments, or remote monitoring sessions{/td}
{td}Farmer immediately sees irrigation status without scrolling or navigating; immediate visual assessment of whether crops need water is guaranteed on every dashboard access{/td}
{td}Survey-extracted stakeholder requirement. Soil moisture received the highest survey score (4.83/5) and was cited by 39% of respondents as their most frequent production-impacting incident — this evidence mandates that soil moisture occupies the most prominent visual position on the dashboard. 'First thing shown' must be formally defined in UX acceptance criteria: the soil moisture widget must appear above the fold on all screen sizes (desktop, tablet, mobile), meaning visible without any scrolling on initial page load. The widget should include: current moisture percentage, threshold indicator (visual marker showing configured min/max setpoints from GMS-23/29), last-reading timestamp, and a color-coded status indicator (green = within range, amber = approaching threshold, red = below/above threshold). Given that GMS-36/39 mandates full mobile functionality, the prominent position must be maintained on mobile viewports (≥360px width). Acceptance: soil moisture widget is the first data element visible on dashboard load across all supported screen sizes; widget displays current value, threshold indicator, and color-coded status; no scrolling required to view on initial load. Cross-references: GMS-30 (Job Story pair, SHR-36 — already Proposed), GMS-10/16 (soil moisture monitoring and irrigation trigger — this is the display layer), GMS-26/32 (auto-stop — status reflected in widget), GMS-36/39 (mobile responsive — position must be maintained).{/td}
{td}{status:PROPOSED|color=Yellow}{/td}
{td}Requirement analyzed and refined. Decomposed into: User = farmer, Action = display soil moisture as the primary/top-priority dashboard widget, Circumstances = any dashboard access event (routine checks, emergencies, remote monitoring), Outcome = immediate irrigation assessment without navigation or scrolling. Confirmed Must Have — highest survey score (4.83/5), 39% cited drought as top incident; prominence is a direct UX mandate. 'First thing shown' defined as above-the-fold on all screen sizes. Widget must include: current value, threshold indicator, timestamp, color-coded status. Mobile prominence maintained per GMS-36/39. Linked to GMS-30 (JS pair, SHR-36 — already Proposed). Moving to Proposed.{/td}
{/tr}
{tr}
{td}SHR-36{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-30}{/td}
{td}Job Story{/td}
{td}Farmer / Greenhouse Operator{/td}
{td}Must Have{/td}
{td}Display soil moisture as the primary/top-priority widget on dashboard load{/td}
{td}When opening the dashboard at any time, especially during daily routine checks{/td}
{td}Operator sees soil moisture status immediately without navigating; irrigation decision can be made at a glance{/td}
{td}Soil moisture scored highest in survey (4.83/5) and 39% cited drought as their top production incident — prominence on dashboard is a direct UX requirement. Soil moisture widget must be visible above the fold on all screen sizes. Acceptance: widget appears in top section of dashboard on both mobile and desktop. Linked to GMS-24 (User Story pair).{/td}
{td}{status:PROPOSED|color=Yellow}{/td}
{td}Requirement analyzed and refined. Decomposed into: User = Farmer/Operator, Action = display soil moisture widget prominently on load, Circumstances = any dashboard open event, Outcome = immediate irrigation assessment without navigation. Survey evidence confirms Must Have priority (4.83/5, 39% incident rate). Acceptance criterion defined: soil moisture widget visible above the fold on all screen sizes. Linked to GMS-24. Moving to Proposed.{/td}
{/tr}
{tr}
{td}SHR-37{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-25}{/td}
{td}User Story{/td}
{td}Greenhouse Owner (abroad){/td}
{td}Must Have{/td}
{td}Remotely trigger irrigation activation from the web browser dashboard while located outside the country{/td}
{td}When the greenhouse owner is abroad for an extended period and an unexpected dry spell occurs at the greenhouse location, requiring immediate manual irrigation intervention that cannot wait for the next scheduled or sensor-triggered cycle{/td}
{td}Crops are protected from drought stress during extended absences; the owner retains manual override capability from any location with internet access; the system bridges the gap between automated triggers and unexpected environmental events{/td}
{td}Survey-extracted stakeholder requirement. One survey respondent explicitly described needing to trigger watering while abroad for extended periods — this directly validates the remote manual override use case. Remote irrigation activation must function reliably over 4G/5G mobile connections (cross-reference GMS-52/58 — the owner may be accessing from a mobile device while abroad). Critical security requirement: remote actuation must be authenticated — GMS-47/48 (TLS/X.509/RBAC) must be in place before this feature is deployed to prevent unauthorized irrigation triggering. Important interaction with automated control: the manual remote trigger must co-exist with threshold-based automation (GMS-16) and schedule-based automation (GMS-22/28) — the system must handle the case where a manual trigger occurs while a scheduled or sensor-triggered cycle is already in progress (either queue or ignore duplicate activation). Auto-stop (GMS-26/32) must still apply to remotely-triggered irrigation — the pump must halt when soil reaches the target setpoint regardless of how the cycle was started. Expert Bragarenco emphasized the importance of industrial-grade relay-based solenoid valve control for remote actuation reliability. The dashboard must provide clear visual feedback: current irrigation status (active/inactive), confirmation upon remote trigger, and current soil moisture reading so the owner can make an informed decision before triggering. Acceptance: authenticated user can trigger irrigation from browser while abroad; confirmation displayed; auto-stop (GMS-26/32) applies; works over 4G/5G; event logged with timestamp, trigger source (manual-remote), and operator identity. Cross-references: GMS-31 (Job Story pair, SHR-38 — already Proposed), GMS-16 (sensor-triggered co-existence), GMS-22/28 (schedule co-existence), GMS-26/32 (auto-stop applies), GMS-47/48 (authentication required), GMS-52/58 (4G connectivity).{/td}
{td}{status:PROPOSED|color=Yellow}{/td}
{td}Requirement analyzed and refined. Decomposed into: User = greenhouse owner abroad, Action = remotely trigger irrigation from browser dashboard, Circumstances = unexpected dry spell during extended international absence, Outcome = crop drought protection via manual override from any location. Confirmed Must Have — survey evidence of abroad use case. Security dependency: authentication (GMS-47/48) required before deployment. Co-existence with GMS-16 (sensor) and GMS-22/28 (schedule) clarified — duplicate activation handling needed. Auto-stop (GMS-26/32) applies to remotely-triggered cycles. Expert Bragarenco confirmed industrial-grade solenoid valve control for reliability. Dashboard must show irrigation status and soil moisture for informed triggering. Event logged with trigger source and operator identity. Linked to GMS-31 (JS pair, SHR-38 — already Proposed). Moving to Proposed.{/td}
{/tr}
{tr}
{td}SHR-38{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-31}{/td}
{td}Job Story{/td}
{td}Greenhouse Owner (off-site / abroad){/td}
{td}Must Have{/td}
{td}Remotely trigger irrigation activation via browser dashboard{/td}
{td}When owner is abroad for an extended period and an unexpected dry spell occurs at the greenhouse{/td}
{td}Irrigation is activated remotely without on-site presence; crops are protected during absence{/td}
{td}Survey: one respondent explicitly required fully autonomous and remote-controllable operation for up to 3 months while abroad. Remote activation must function reliably over 4G/5G (cross-reference GMS-52/58). Requires authentication controls (GMS-47/48) to prevent unauthorized triggering. Manual remote override must co-exist with automated threshold-based control. Linked to GMS-25 (User Story pair).{/td}
{td}{status:PROPOSED|color=Yellow}{/td}
{td}Requirement analyzed and refined. Decomposed into: User = greenhouse owner abroad, Action = remotely trigger irrigation via browser, Circumstances = extended absence with unexpected dry spell, Outcome = crop protection without on-site presence. Key dependency identified: must work over 4G/5G (GMS-52/58) and requires secure authentication (GMS-47/48). Remote manual override must not conflict with automated threshold control — clarified for SRS use case definition. Linked to GMS-25. Moving to Proposed.{/td}
{/tr}
{tr}
{td}SHR-39{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-26}{/td}
{td}User Story{/td}
{td}Farmer{/td}
{td}Must Have{/td}
{td}Automatically halt any active irrigation cycle when the soil moisture sensor reading reaches the user-configured target threshold{/td}
{td}During any active irrigation cycle — whether triggered by sensor threshold breach (GMS-16), timed schedule (GMS-22/28), or manual remote activation (GMS-25/31) — at the moment soil moisture reaches the configured target setpoint{/td}
{td}Over-watering is prevented; water waste is eliminated; root damage from waterlogging is avoided; the irrigation system is self-regulating regardless of the trigger source{/td}
{td}Survey-extracted stakeholder requirement. 17% of respondents cited irrigation failures as a direct production problem — automatic cutoff is the essential safety mechanism that completes the irrigation automation loop. Without auto-stop, every automated irrigation trigger (sensor-based GMS-16, schedule-based GMS-22/28, remote manual GMS-25/31) carries a risk of over-watering if conditions change during the cycle. The target moisture threshold must be user-configurable per crop type (cross-reference GMS-23/29 — crop-specific setpoints). The edge controller must execute the cutoff locally and immediately, even during cloud connectivity loss — this is a critical subset of the offline autonomy requirement (Project Charter O5). Given that the auto-stop function involves halting an actuator to prevent crop damage, it is a safety-critical control path. Sensor read latency must be accounted for: if the soil moisture sensor has a settling time after water application, the auto-stop logic should prevent premature cutoff by requiring N consecutive readings at or above the target before halting. This hysteresis behavior prevents oscillating on/off cycles (chattering). Acceptance: irrigation stops within 30 seconds of soil moisture reaching the configured target setpoint; applies to all trigger sources (sensor, schedule, manual remote); executes locally during cloud outage; event logged with timestamp, trigger source, soil moisture at start and at cutoff. Cross-references: GMS-32 (Job Story pair, SHR-40 — already Proposed), GMS-16 (sensor-triggered irrigation — auto-stop completes the loop), GMS-22/28 (scheduled irrigation — auto-stop overrides schedule if soil is wet), GMS-25/31 (remote manual — auto-stop still applies), GMS-23/29 (configurable target setpoint).{/td}
{td}{status:PROPOSED|color=Yellow}{/td}
{td}Requirement analyzed and refined. Decomposed into: User = farmer, Action = automatically halt irrigation when soil moisture reaches target, Circumstances = any active irrigation cycle regardless of trigger source (sensor/schedule/manual), Outcome = prevention of over-watering, water waste, and root damage. Confirmed Must Have — 17% cited irrigation failures as production problem; auto-stop completes the irrigation automation loop. Safety-critical control path: edge controller must execute cutoff locally during cloud outage. Hysteresis recommended to prevent chattering (N consecutive readings at setpoint before halt). Threshold user-configurable per crop (GMS-23/29). Acceptance: stops within 30s of reaching setpoint; applies to all trigger sources; offline execution; event logged. Linked to GMS-32 (JS pair, SHR-40 — already Proposed). Moving to Proposed.{/td}
{/tr}
{tr}
{td}SHR-40{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-32}{/td}
{td}Job Story{/td}
{td}Farmer{/td}
{td}Must Have{/td}
{td}Automatically halt irrigation when soil moisture sensor reading reaches the configured target threshold{/td}
{td}During any active irrigation cycle, whether sensor-triggered or schedule-triggered{/td}
{td}Irrigation stops at the correct moisture level; overwatering, root damage, and water waste are prevented{/td}
{td}Automatic cutoff is the logical complement to automatic start (GMS-16/31). Survey: 17% cited irrigation failures as a direct production problem. The target threshold must be user-configurable (cross-reference GMS-23/29 — crop-specific setpoints). Critical: the edge controller must execute the cutoff locally even during cloud connectivity loss — this is an offline autonomy requirement. Acceptance: irrigation stops within 30 seconds of moisture reaching the setpoint. Linked to GMS-26 (User Story pair).{/td}
{td}{status:PROPOSED|color=Yellow}{/td}
{td}Requirement analyzed and refined. Decomposed into: User = farmer, Action = automatic irrigation cutoff at target threshold, Circumstances = any active irrigation cycle (sensor or scheduled), Outcome = prevention of overwatering and root damage. Critical offline autonomy dependency identified: edge controller must execute cutoff locally without cloud connectivity. Threshold must be user-configurable per crop type (GMS-23/29). Acceptance criterion: irrigation stops within 30 seconds of reaching setpoint. Linked to GMS-26. Moving to Proposed.{/td}
{/tr}
{tr}
{td}SHR-41{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-27}{/td}
{td}User Story{/td}
{td}Farmer{/td}
{td}Could Have{/td}
{td}Generate differentiated alert notifications for heat events (temperature exceeding upper threshold) and cold/frost events (temperature dropping below lower threshold), each carrying distinct alert type labels and recommended response guidance{/td}
{td}When temperature thresholds are breached in either direction — during summer overheating events when internal greenhouse temperatures can reach 60–80°C (expert Bragarenco interview) or during winter frost periods when external temperatures drop to -15°C{/td}
{td}Farmer immediately knows the type of thermal problem and can take the correct corrective action without needing to interpret raw temperature data; heat events trigger ventilation-oriented responses while frost events trigger heating-oriented responses{/td}
{td}Survey-extracted stakeholder requirement. Respondents described needing to distinguish heat and cold events — the distinction improves response accuracy but a single threshold alert already covers both scenarios at the baseline (GMS-15/21). Classification: Could Have per WP4.2 analysis — the baseline alert system (GMS-15/21) already alerts on any threshold breach, so the differentiation adds UX value but is not functionally blocking. The implementation is straightforward: the alert generation logic (GMS-15/21) already knows the parameter name and breach direction (above upper vs below lower threshold) — adding a label ('HEAT ALERT' vs 'FROST ALERT') and a recommended action string ('Check ventilation' vs 'Check heating') requires minimal additional development. Expert Bragarenco confirmed that summer internal temperatures can reach 60–80°C and that motor-controlled ventilation is essential — a heat-specific alert reinforces this operational reality. The frost response and heat response require fundamentally different actions from the operator, so undifferentiated alerts force the operator to check the dashboard for context, adding latency to the response. If implemented, the alert type label should also flow to push/SMS notifications (GMS-40/41) so off-site operators know which action to take without opening the dashboard. Peer review R4 (WP4.2, Vremere Adrian) flagged that this requirement does not cover rate-of-change events (e.g., rapid temperature drop) — this is acknowledged and explicitly deferred to a future phase. Acceptance: heat threshold breach generates alert labeled 'HEAT' with ventilation guidance; frost threshold breach generates alert labeled 'FROST' with heating guidance; alert type included in push/SMS if GMS-40/41 is active. Cross-references: GMS-33 (Job Story pair, SHR-42), GMS-15/21 (baseline alert framework — differentiation builds on top), GMS-17 (heating/ventilation autoresponse — alert type mirrors actuator action), GMS-40/41 (push/SMS — alert type should propagate).{/td}
{td}{status:PROPOSED|color=Yellow}{/td}
{td}Requirement analyzed and refined. Decomposed into: User = farmer, Action = receive differentiated heat vs frost alerts with specific type labels and response guidance, Circumstances = summer overheating (up to 60–80°C internally per Bragarenco) or winter frost (down to -15°C externally), Outcome = immediate identification of thermal problem type enabling correct corrective action. Classified as Could Have — baseline alert (GMS-15/21) already covers threshold breach; differentiation adds UX accuracy but is not functionally blocking. Implementation is low-effort: alert logic already knows breach direction — adding type label and response guidance is minimal. Expert testimony supports the operational value. Peer review R4: rate-of-change detection deferred to future phase. Alert type should propagate to push/SMS (GMS-40/41) if implemented. Linked to GMS-33 (JS pair, SHR-42). Moving to Proposed.{/td}
{/tr}
{tr}
{td}SHR-42{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-33}{/td}
{td}Job Story{/td}
{td}Farmer{/td}
{td}Could Have{/td}
{td}Generate and deliver a frost-specific alert notification — distinct from heat warnings — when nighttime temperature drops unexpectedly below the configured lower threshold, carrying a 'FROST' label and recommended heating-related corrective action{/td}
{td}During nighttime hours when temperatures can drop unexpectedly in Moldova's continental climate (winter lows reaching -15°C), particularly during spring and autumn transition periods when frost events are less predictable and crops are most vulnerable to sudden cold damage{/td}
{td}Farmer receives a clearly distinguished frost alert enabling the correct cold-response action (check heating, close ventilation) rather than a generic temperature warning that could be confused with a heat event requiring the opposite response{/td}
{td}Job Story counterpart to GMS-27 (SHR-41, already Proposed). This Job Story emphasizes the nighttime frost scenario — the most dangerous context for undifferentiated alerts because the operator is likely asleep and may be woken by a push notification (GMS-40/41). If the notification simply says 'temperature threshold exceeded,' the operator must open the dashboard to determine whether to activate heating or ventilation — these are opposite responses, and a wrong decision can worsen the problem. Moldova's continental climate makes nighttime frost a recurring seasonal risk, especially during March–April and October–November transitions when crops are still active. Implementation: the alert system (GMS-15/21) already captures breach direction — adding a 'FROST' label and a 'Recommended: check heating system' guidance string is a low-effort addition with high UX value for nighttime scenarios. If push/SMS (GMS-40/41) is implemented, the frost label and guidance must be included in the notification payload. Peer review R4 (WP4.2, Vremere Adrian) flagged that this requirement does not cover rate-of-change events (e.g., rapid temperature drop) — this is acknowledged and explicitly deferred to a future phase. Acceptance: nighttime frost breach generates alert labeled 'FROST' distinct from 'HEAT'; includes recommended corrective action; frost label propagates to push/SMS if active; alert appears within ≤60s of breach. Cross-references: GMS-27 (User Story pair, SHR-41), GMS-15/21 (baseline alert framework), GMS-17 (automated heating response — frost alert mirrors heating actuation), GMS-40/41 (push/SMS — label must propagate for nighttime notifications).{/td}
{td}{status:PROPOSED|color=Yellow}{/td}
{td}Requirement analyzed and refined. Decomposed into: User = farmer (likely asleep during nighttime frost), Action = frost-specific alert distinct from heat warning with corrective guidance, Circumstances = unexpected nighttime temperature drop in Moldova’s continental climate (winter lows -15°C, spring/autumn transition frost risk), Outcome = correct cold-response action taken without dashboard consultation. Classified as Could Have — Job Story pair to GMS-27 (SHR-41). High UX value for nighttime scenarios where operator is woken by notification. Implementation low-effort: breach direction already captured by alert system. Peer review R4: rate-of-change detection deferred to future phase. Frost label and guidance must propagate to push/SMS if GMS-40/41 is active. Acceptance: frost-labeled alert within ≤60s; distinct from heat; guidance included. Linked to GMS-27 (US pair, SHR-41). Moving to Proposed.{/td}
{/tr}
{tr}
{td}SHR-43{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-52}{/td}
{td}User Story{/td}
{td}Rural Farmer{/td}
{td}Must Have{/td}
{td}Use all system features reliably over a 4G/5G mobile data connection{/td}
{td}When located in rural Moldova where 55.6% of greenhouse sites rely on mobile data and only 33.3% have fixed broadband{/td}
{td}System fully accessible and functional over mobile network; no fixed broadband required{/td}
{td}Critical infrastructure requirement backed by survey data. Must include: MQTT/HTTPS optimized for high-latency mobile links, lightweight dashboard payload, edge caching for connectivity interruptions. Acceptance criteria: all core features functional on 4G with latency up to 200ms. Also covers the 11.1% with no stable connection — edge offline fallback is complementary.{/td}
{td}{status:PROPOSED|color=Yellow}{/td}
{td}Analyzed: rural farmer dependent on mobile data, action is system usage over 4G/5G, circumstance is rural Moldova with limited broadband, outcome is full functionality without wired connection. Technical architecture implications noted. Moving to Proposed.{/td}
{/tr}
{tr}
{td}SHR-44{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-58}{/td}
{td}Job Story{/td}
{td}Rural Farmer{/td}
{td}Must Have{/td}
{td}Connect to and use all GMS system features reliably over a 4G/5G mobile data connection{/td}
{td}When located in a rural area of Moldova where 55.6% of greenhouse sites rely exclusively on mobile data and only 33.3% have fixed broadband, with 11.1% having no stable connection at all{/td}
{td}Full system functionality is available without requiring a fixed broadband installation; the majority of target users are not excluded from cloud features{/td}
{td}This is the Job Story counterpart to GMS-52 (SHR-43 — already Proposed). Critical infrastructure requirement directly supported by survey data. Technical architecture implications: communication stack must use MQTT or HTTPS optimized for high-latency mobile links; dashboard payload must be lightweight (cross-reference GMS-57/59); edge caching must be implemented on the embedded controller to handle connectivity interruptions — this also covers the 11.1% with no stable connection. Offline edge fallback must maintain local autonomous control for 72h per Project Charter O5. Acceptance: all core features functional on 4G with latency up to 200ms; edge controller maintains autonomous operation during connectivity loss. Cross-references: GMS-52 (User Story pair, SHR-43), GMS-57/59 (bandwidth optimization), GMS-36/39 (mobile-responsive design).{/td}
{td}{status:PROPOSED|color=Yellow}{/td}
{td}Requirement analyzed and refined. Decomposed into: User = rural farmer, Action = use all system features over 4G/5G mobile connection, Circumstances = rural Moldova with mobile-only connectivity (55.6% of sites), Outcome = full functionality without fixed broadband requirement. Confirmed as Job Story pair to GMS-52 (already Proposed). Architecture implications logged: MQTT/HTTPS over mobile, lightweight payloads, edge caching for interruptions. 72h offline autonomy required per Project Charter O5. Acceptance: all core features at ≤200ms 4G latency; edge offline fallback operational. Cross-references added to GMS-57/59 (bandwidth) and GMS-36/39 (mobile design). Moving to Proposed.{/td}
{/tr}
{tr}
{td}SHR-45{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-57}{/td}
{td}User Story{/td}
{td}Small-scale Farmer (mobile data plan){/td}
{td}Should Have{/td}
{td}Optimize dashboard for minimal data transfer and fast load on constrained mobile connections{/td}
{td}When accessing the GMS dashboard on a limited or pay-per-MB mobile data plan in a rural area{/td}
{td}Dashboard is usable without excessive data consumption; operational cost of using the system is kept low{/td}
{td}Survey: 55.6% of respondents rely on mobile data as their primary connection. Bandwidth optimization is important for usability but does not block core functionality — correctly classified as Should Have. Acceptance: initial dashboard page load transfers under 200 KB; large historical charts are lazy-loaded and not fetched on dashboard open. Implementation note: compress sensor payloads, minimize static asset size, avoid auto-loading full data history. Cross-reference: GMS-36 (mobile responsive design), GMS-52/58 (4G/5G connectivity Must Have). Linked to GMS-59 (Job Story pair).{/td}
{td}{status:PROPOSED|color=Yellow}{/td}
{td}Requirement analyzed and refined. Decomposed into: User = small-scale farmer on mobile data plan, Action = optimize dashboard for minimal data transfer and fast load, Circumstances = limited or pay-per-MB mobile connection in rural area, Outcome = usable and cost-effective dashboard on constrained plans. Acceptance criterion defined: initial page load under 200 KB transferred; historical charts lazy-loaded on demand. Implementation guidance noted: compress payloads, minimize assets, avoid auto-fetching full history on open. Cross-references added to GMS-36 (mobile responsive) and GMS-52/58 (connectivity). Linked to GMS-59. Moving to Proposed.{/td}
{/tr}
{tr}
{td}SHR-46{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-59}{/td}
{td}Job Story{/td}
{td}Small-scale Farmer{/td}
{td}Should Have{/td}
{td}Deliver dashboard pages that respond quickly and consume minimal bandwidth on slow or metered connections{/td}
{td}When checking greenhouse status on a limited mobile data plan, potentially in a low-signal rural area{/td}
{td}System is cost-effective to use on limited plans; pages are responsive even on slower connections{/td}
{td}Companion Job Story to GMS-57 (User Story pair). Together, GMS-57 and GMS-59 define the performance budget for the web dashboard. Acceptance: page load time under 3 seconds on a standard 4G connection; dashboard remains functional on connections as slow as 1 Mbps. Dashboard should not auto-refresh heavy payloads — allow user-controlled or interval-based lightweight polling instead. Cross-reference: GMS-52/58 (4G/5G connectivity Must Have) establishes the baseline connectivity assumption this requirement builds on.{/td}
{td}{status:PROPOSED|color=Yellow}{/td}
{td}Requirement analyzed and refined. Decomposed into: User = small-scale farmer on mobile data plan, Action = deliver fast-loading low-bandwidth dashboard pages, Circumstances = limited mobile data plan in rural/low-signal area, Outcome = cost-effective and responsive system usage. Together with GMS-57, these two requirements define the full performance budget for the dashboard. Acceptance criteria: page load under 3 seconds on 4G; functional at 1 Mbps minimum. Auto-refresh of heavy payloads should be avoided — lightweight polling recommended instead. Cross-reference added to GMS-52/58 as connectivity baseline dependency. Linked to GMS-57. Moving to Proposed.{/td}
{/tr}
{tr}
{td}SHR-47{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-36}{/td}
{td}User Story{/td}
{td}Small-scale Farmer{/td}
{td}Must Have{/td}
{td}Access and operate all system features via smartphone browser{/td}
{td}When managing greenhouse without access to a desktop computer, which is the norm for 55.6% of surveyed operators relying on mobile data{/td}
{td}Full system usability on mobile without degradation of functionality{/td}
{td}Mobile-responsive design is a hard requirement based on survey data: 55.6% use smartphones as primary device. 'Look and work well' must be defined: minimum viewport support (e.g., 360px), touch-friendly controls, no horizontal scrolling. Acceptance criteria should include testing on common Android/iOS screen sizes.{/td}
{td}{status:PROPOSED|color=Yellow}{/td}
{td}Analyzed: small-scale farmer needs full mobile access. Circumstance is daily greenhouse management on smartphone. Clarification added re: specific responsive design targets. Moving to Proposed.{/td}
{/tr}
{tr}
{td}SHR-48{/td}
{td}{jira:GMS-39}{/td}
{td}Job Story{/td}
{td}Small-scale Farmer (on the move){/td}
{td}Must Have{/td}
{td}Perform all management actions (monitor, configure, trigger irrigation) via smartphone{/td}
